#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "The bash shell allows for the use of **loops**. These structures allow for the execution of **a block of commands several times** (from 0 to infinity) according to a statically defined value, dynamically or on condition:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "`while`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "`until`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "`for`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "`select`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "Whatever the loop used, the commands to be repeated are placed **between the words** `do` and `done`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "The while conditional loop structure"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `while` / `do` / `done` structure evaluates the command placed after `while`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "If this command is true (`$? = 0`), the commands placed between `do` and `done` are executed. The script then returns to the beginning to evaluate the command again.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "When the evaluated command is false (`$? != 0`), the shell resumes the execution of the script at the first command after done.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "Syntax of the conditional loop structure `while`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:48
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"while command\n"
"do\n"
"  command if $? = 0\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:56
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example using the `while` conditional structure:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:57
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"while [[ -e /etc/passwd ]]\n"
"do\n"
"  echo \"The file exists\"\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:65
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the evaluated command does not vary, the loop will be infinite and the shell will never execute the commands placed after the script. This can be intentional, but it can also be an error. So you have to be **very careful with the commands that manage the loop and find a way to get out of it**.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:67
#, no-wrap
msgid "To get out of a `while` loop, you have to make sure that the command being evaluated is no longer true, which is not always possible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "There are commands that allow you to change the behavior of a loop:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "`exit`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "`break`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "`continue`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "The exit command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:77
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `exit` command ends the execution of the script.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "Syntax of the `exit` command :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:80
#, no-wrap
msgid "exit [n]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:85
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example using the `exit` command :\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:86
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"bash # to avoid being disconnected after the \"exit 1\n"
"exit 1\n"
"echo $?\n"
"1\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:95
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The `exit` command ends the script immediately. It is possible to specify the return code of the script by giving it as an argument (from `0` to `255`).\n"
"If no argument is given, the return code of the last command of the script will be passed to the `$?` variable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:96
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `break` / `continue` commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:99
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `break` command allows you to interrupt the loop by going to the first command after `done`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:101
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `continue` command allows you to restart the loop by going back to the first command after `done`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:102
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"while [[ -d / ]]                                                  î² INT â î² 17s ï\n"
"do\n"
"  echo \"Do you want to continue? (yes/no)\"\n"
"  read ans\n"
"  [[ $ans = \"yes\" ]] && continue\n"
"  [[ $ans = \"no\" ]] && break\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:112
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `true` / `false` commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:115
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `true` command always returns `true` while the `false` command always returns `false`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:116
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"true\n"
"echo $?\n"
"0\n"
"false\n"
"echo $?\n"
"1\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:126
#, no-wrap
msgid "Used as a condition of a loop, they allow for either an execution of an infinite loop or the deactivation of this loop.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:129
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"while true\n"
"do\n"
"  echo \"Do you want to continue? (yes/no)\"\n"
"  read ans\n"
"  [[ $ans = \"yes\" ]] && continue\n"
"  [[ $ans = \"no\" ]] && break\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:139
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `until` conditional loop structure"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:142
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `until` / `do` / `done` structure evaluates the command placed after `until`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:144
#, no-wrap
msgid "If this command is false (`$? != 0`), the commands placed between `do` and `done` are executed. The script then returns to the beginning to evaluate the command again.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:146
#, no-wrap
msgid "When the evaluated command is true (`$? = 0`), the shell resumes the execution of the script at the first command after `done`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:148
#, no-wrap
msgid "Syntax of the conditional loop structure `until`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:149
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"until command\n"
"do\n"
"  command if $? != 0\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:157
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example of the use of the conditional structure `until`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:158
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"until [[ -e test_until ]]\n"
"do\n"
"  echo \"The file does not exist\"\n"
"  touch test_until\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:166
#, no-wrap
msgid "The alternative choice structure `select`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:169
#, no-wrap
msgid "The structure `select` / `do` / `done` allows for the display of a menu with several choices and an input request.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:171
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each item in the list has a numbered choice. When you enter a choice, the value chosen is assigned to the variable placed after `select` (created for this purpose).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:173
#, no-wrap
msgid "It then executes the commands placed between `do` and `done` with this value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:176
#, no-wrap
msgid "The variable `PS3` contains the invitation to enter the choice;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:176
#, no-wrap
msgid "The variable `REPLY` will return the number of the choice.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:178
#, no-wrap
msgid "A `break` command is needed to exit the loop.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:182
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `select` structure is very useful for small and simple menus. To customize a more complete display, the `echo` and `read` commands must be used in a `while` loop.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:184
#, no-wrap
msgid "Syntax of the conditional loop structure `select`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:185
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"PS3=\"Your choice:\"\n"
"select variable in var1 var2 var3\n"
"do\n"
"  commands\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:194
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example of the use of the conditional structure `select`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:195
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"PS3=\"Your choice: \"\n"
"select choice in coffee tea chocolate\n"
"do\n"
"  echo \"You have chosen the $REPLY: $choice\"\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:204
#, no-wrap
msgid "If this script is run, it shows something like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1) '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:205
#, no-wrap
msgid "Coffee\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2) '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:205
#, no-wrap
msgid "Tea\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:205
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"3) Chocolate\n"
"Your choice : 2\n"
"You have chosen choice 2: Tea\n"
"Your choice:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:214
#, no-wrap
msgid "The loop structure on a list of values `for`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:217
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `for` / `do` / `done` structure assigns the first element of the list to the variable placed after `for` (created on this occasion). It then executes the commands placed between `do` and `done` with this value. The script then returns to the beginning to assign the next element of the list to the working variable. When the last element has been used, the shell resumes execution at the first command after `done`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:219
#, no-wrap
msgid "Syntax of the loop structure on list of values `for`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:220
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"for variable in list\n"
"do\n"
"  commands\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:228
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example of using the conditional structure `for`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:229
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"for file in /home /etc/passwd /root/fic.txt\n"
"do\n"
"  file $file\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:237
#, no-wrap
msgid "Any command producing a list of values can be placed after the `in` using a sub-execution.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:240
#, no-wrap
msgid "With the variable `IFS` containing `$' \\t\\n'`, the `for` loop will take **each word** of the result of this command as a list of elements to loop on.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:240
#, no-wrap
msgid "With the `IFS` variable containing `$'\\t\\n'` (i.e. without spaces), the `for` loop will take each line of the result of this command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:242
#, no-wrap
msgid "This can be the files in a directory. In this case, the variable will take as a value each of the words of the file names present:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:243
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"for file in $(ls -d /tmp/*)\n"
"do\n"
"  echo $file\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:251
#, no-wrap
msgid "It can be a file. In this case, the variable will take as a value each word contained in the file browsed, from the beginning to the end:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:252
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"cat my_file.txt\n"
"first line\n"
"second line\n"
"third line\n"
"for LINE in $(cat my_file.txt); do echo $LINE; done\n"
"first\n"
"line\n"
"second\n"
"line\n"
"third line\n"
"line\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:267
#, no-wrap
msgid "To read a file line by line, you must modify the value of the `IFS` environment variable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/07-loops.md:268
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"IFS=$'\\t\\n'\n"
"for LINE in $(cat my_file.txt); do echo $LINE; done\n"
"first line\n"
"second line\n"
"third line\n"
msgstr ""
